TOXIC ALGAE - NORTH CAROLINA: AN UPDATE
========================================
[see 951012]
From: Peter_Cowen@ncsu.edu
Date: March 29, 1997
Because of the recent release of the book "Blood in the Waters", there has
been a great deal of discussion lately in the national news concerning
North Carolina waters and toxic algae.
At the present time, four things are clear: 1) There has been no new fish
kills recently, so much of this "news" is material discussed on ProMED-mail
in 1995 2) The present concern is media-mediated i.e. the book and
newsmagazines, TV and otherwise. 3) Physicians in the area of the Nuese
River are concerned about rashes which don't appear to have a known cause.
These rashes could be related to _Pfiesteria piscida_ , could be caused by
something else or could be occuring at no greater incidence than in the
past. 4) To date all evidence is antecodotal. There are proper
epidemiologic studies underway at the medical school at East Carolina
University and other studies at Duke. No conclusions either way yet.
ProMED-mail will keep you updated when results become available.
This present round of worry is another instance where the media spawns
questions faster than controlled studies can offer answers, so there is a
great deal of confusion generated for the public from time to time. So
goes the battle. I hope this update helps.
--
Peter Cowen DVM, PhD
ProMED-AHEAD Moderator
peter_cowen@ncsu.edu
