Date: Wed, 11 Oct 1995 09:59:00 -0500 (EST)
From: Evelyn Studer <ESTUDER@fhi.org>
NORTH CAROLINA ISSUES HEALTH WARNING RELATED TO TOXIC ALGAE
===========================================================
According to a newspaper article (October 7) in the Raleigh (NC)
News and Observer, a health warning, "the first of its type ever
issued in North Carolina, advises people not to swim, fish or
come in contact with waters where a toxic algae has been
attacking menhaden and other fish." Although the association
between the fish kills, caused by Pfiesteria algae, and human
illness is not definite, there have been puzzling symptoms in
some people exposed to the affected fish. Two NC State
University researchers became ill following exposure to the algae
in the lab in 1993. One of the researchers experienced severe
mental impairment. In "recent weeks, some fishermen and divers
on the lower Neuse [River] have developed sores and infections
after being in the water".
"First discovered in 1991, the microscopic Pfiesteria has been
described as a cross between a plant and an animal. In its
predatory stage, the algae poisons fish with a mysterious toxin,
then eats its prey, leaving behind telltale red and black sores."
"Like other forms of algae, Pfiesteria appears to be stimulated
by nutrients such as phosphorus and nitrogen, although the
interaction is not fully understood. Such nutrients come from
farms fertilizers, livestock waste, air pollution and municipal
sewage."
State officials are conducting a health survey of people exposed
to the recent fish kills. The contact person is Dr. Peter Morris
at (919)715-6422.
From: Evelyn Studer, estuder@fhi.org.
